# gate-paths — the ONE canonical list of "the gate layer" for this repository.
#
# This file is the single source of truth for which paths, when changed in a pull
# request, require an independent gate-review before they may merge to main (see
# CONTRIBUTING.md "Governance"). `gate-review-check.py` reads THIS file. The policy
# prose (CONTRIBUTING.md, gate-review-prompt.md) may show an ILLUSTRATIVE list for the
# reader, but it is explicitly non-authoritative — THIS file is what gates, and the
# prose says so. (A gate's self-description diverging from what it actually does is the
# exact failure class this layer exists to catch; here the machine list is canonical
# and the prose is labelled illustrative, so the two cannot silently disagree.)
#
# Why these paths are "the gates that guard the suite": each one can pass CI green
# while silently weakening or mis-describing a check. CI green is necessary but not
# sufficient for them; they additionally require human/independent judgement.
#
# Matching semantics (kept deliberately small and testable):
#   - a line ending in "/"      -> directory subtree: matches any changed path that
#                                   starts with that prefix (e.g. "tests/").
#   - a line containing "*"      -> fnmatch against the full path AND the basename
#                                   (e.g. "lint-*.py" matches "lint-skill-count.py").
#   - any other line             -> exact full-path match (repo-root-relative).
# Blank lines and lines starting with "#" are ignored.

# --- Build / release orchestration -------------------------------------------------
release-gate.sh
build-skills.sh
pkgtools.py

# --- Validators and the version/changelog gate -------------------------------------
validate_skill.py
check-version.py

# --- Suite lints (current AND any future lint-*.py) --------------------------------
lint-*.py

# --- The shared documentation verifier + the CI gate that ships INSIDE every .skill -
# shared/verify.py is the engine; shared/ci/ (verify-docs.yml + the pre-commit config) is the
# docs-as-code gate build-skills.sh copies into every package and the manifest hashes — weakening
# either silently weakens the gate every consumer runs.
shared/verify.py
shared/ci/

# --- The gates that guard the gates ------------------------------------------------
tests/

# --- CI + the governance / enforcement layer itself (self-protecting) --------------
# Changing how merges are gated is itself a gate-layer change: a weakened workflow, a narrowed
# gate-paths list, a softened policy, a relaxed check, or a loosened verdict contract must not slip
# in unreviewed. So the enforcement layer guards itself. (docs/SETTINGS.md is the RECORD of the live
# ruleset, not the ruleset itself — gated so the documented policy can't be softened unreviewed.)
.github/
gate-review-check.py
gate-review-prompt.md
gate-reviews/TEMPLATE.md
gate-reviews/README.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
docs/SETTINGS.md

# --- Deliberately NOT gated (recorded so the boundary is explicit, not an oversight) ----------------
# - CHANGELOG.md: a historical log that changes every release; gating it is friction, and it cannot
#   weaken a check (the canonical governance docs above are gated). It DESCRIBES, it does not enforce.
# - gate-reviews/<NNNN>-*.md (the verdict records themselves): NOT gated, to avoid a self-referential
#   loop (every gate PR adds one). They are append-only history by policy (CONTRIBUTING "Governance");
#   editing a past verdict is discouraged and, if done, is itself a gate-review-worthy act.
# - shared/house-style.md, shared/render-contract.md: authoring standards (see CONTRIBUTING). Add any
#   of these if you want maximal coverage; the omission is a documented choice, reviewed via this file.
